---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const vulns = [
  { n: '01', title: 'SQL injection', note: 'Still the most common class in 2026.', sample: 'fmt.sprintf to directly embed user-controllable string variables into sql queries creating critical sql injection vulnerabilities' },
  { n: '02', title: 'Path traversal', note: 'Often via unsanitized URL parameters used to construct file paths.', sample: 'path traversal vulnerability in resolvepath. the function allows absolute paths (e.g. etc passwd) to be used directly completely bypassing the repository directory jail' },
  { n: '03', title: 'Missing authorization', note: 'Endpoints without permission checks, or routers that lost their auth dependency during a refactor.', sample: 'the authorization dependencies have been removed from the api_keys clients and marketplace routers. previously these routers were protected by depends(require_scopes(...))' },
  { n: '04', title: 'XSS via unescaped attributes', note: 'User-controlled values written into HTML attributes without escaping.', sample: 'html for the tooltips concatenando diretamente valores lidos de atributos data- em um atributo title sem qualquer tipo de sanitizacao' },
  { n: '05', title: 'SSRF', note: 'URL parameters fed directly into outbound HTTP requests, allowing attackers to reach internal services.', sample: 'the getmerchantid function is vulnerable to server-side request forgery (ssrf). it directly uses the link parameter which can be controlled by a user in an axios.get call without validation' },
  { n: '06', title: 'Hardcoded secrets in source', note: 'Tokens, API keys, and access credentials committed alongside code.', sample: 'hardcoding the cf-access-client-id and cf-access-client-secret directly into the source code is a critical security vulnerability. these credentials will be committed to the version control history permanently' },
  { n: '07', title: 'Open redirect', note: 'Redirect helpers that block obvious schemes but miss protocol-relative URLs.', sample: 'the safe_return_to_path method is vulnerable to open redirection. it correctly blocks schemes like http and javascript but it allows protocol-relative urls such as evil.com' },
  { n: '08', title: 'Sensitive data exposure in logs', note: 'Raw error objects, internal IDs, or full request payloads logged for debugging and never sanitized.', sample: 'the error message in banking.ts (lines 166-169) leaks internal workspaceid when a transaction is found but does not belong to the requesting store. this information leak allows verifying the existence of settlements' },
  { n: '09', title: 'Prompt injection', isNew: true, note: 'New top-10 entrant in 2026. System prompts that concatenate user-controlled strings without delimiters or sanitization.', sample: 'el prompt del sistema concatena directamente datos potencialmente controlados por el usuario sin ningun tipo de delimitador o instruccion de saneamiento. esto crea una vulnerabilidad de inyeccion de prompt' },
  { n: '10', title: 'Default credentials', note: 'Services deployed with well-known default usernames and passwords.', sample: 'the rabbitmq service is configured with the default well-known credentials guest guest. this is a significant security risk. the guest user is intended for local development' },
  { n: '11', title: 'Command injection', note: 'User input passed unsanitized into shell commands.', sample: 'the basebranch parameter is used directly in a shell command without sanitization creating a command injection vulnerability. an attacker who can control the value can execute arbitrary commands' },
  { n: '12', title: 'PostMessage origin not validated', note: 'Window message listeners that process events from any origin.', sample: 'the message event listener is missing a crucial security check to validate the origin of the incoming event. without verifying event.origin the application will process messages sent from any website' },
];
---

<Layout
  title="The 2026 vulnerability landscape · State of AI Code Review"
  description="The top security vulnerability classes AI code review caught on production pull requests in 2026. SQL injection is still #1. Prompt injection enters the top 10."
  runningHead="§ 02 Vulnerabilities"
  page="Plate II"
>

  <section class="max-w-[1280px] mx-auto px-8 pt-16 md:pt-20 pb-12">
    <div class="grid grid-cols-12 gap-8 items-start">
      <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-2">
        <div class="font-display italic text-oxblood-500 leading-none reveal reveal-1" style="font-size: clamp(5rem, 8vw, 7.5rem);">II</div>
        <div class="tracked text-ink-500 mt-3 reveal reveal-1">Plate II</div>
      </div>
      <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-7">
        <div class="tracked text-ink-500 mb-4 reveal reveal-2">Chapter § 02 · Vulnerabilities</div>
        <h1 class="font-display leading-[0.98] tracking-tight text-ink-900 reveal reveal-2" style="font-size: clamp(3rem, 7vw, 6rem);">
          The 2026 vulnerability <span class="italic">landscape.</span>
        </h1>
      </div>
      <aside class="col-span-12 md:col-span-3 md:pt-8 reveal reveal-3">
        <div class="border-l border-ink-900 pl-5">
          <p class="text-ink-700 leading-[1.6] text-[15px]">
            Drawn from 7,483 accepted security findings across 200 organizations. SQL injection is still the most common class. A new category, prompt injection, enters the top 10 in 2026 as more applications expose LLM-backed endpoints.
          </p>
        </div>
      </aside>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="max-w-[1280px] mx-auto px-8 pb-32">
    <div class="border-t-2 border-ink-900">
      {vulns.map((v) => (
        <article class="border-b border-paper-300 py-12">
          <div class="grid grid-cols-12 gap-8">
            <div class="col-span-2 md:col-span-1">
              <div class="font-display italic text-oxblood-500 leading-none" style="font-size: clamp(2rem, 3vw, 3rem);">{v.n}</div>
            </div>
            <div class="col-span-10 md:col-span-7">
              <div class="flex items-baseline gap-4 flex-wrap mb-3">
                <h2 class="font-display text-ink-900 tracking-tight leading-[1.05]" style="font-size: clamp(1.5rem, 2.25vw, 2.25rem);">{v.title}</h2>
                {v.isNew && (
                  <span class="font-mono text-[10px] tracking-[0.22em] uppercase bg-oxblood-500 text-paper-50 px-2.5 py-1">New in 2026</span>
                )}
              </div>
              <p class="text-ink-700 leading-[1.7] mt-2 max-w-prose text-[16px]">{v.note}</p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-4">
              <div class="margin-note">Excerpt · review comment</div>
              <blockquote class="font-mono text-[12.5px] leading-[1.7] text-ink-700 mt-2 pl-4 border-l-2 border-oxblood-500">
                {v.sample}
              </blockquote>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="max-w-[1280px] mx-auto px-8 pb-20">
    <div class="grid grid-cols-12 gap-8">
      <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-3">
        <div class="tracked text-ink-500">Note on prompt injection</div>
      </div>
      <div class="col-span-12 md:col-span-9">
        <p class="font-display italic text-ink-700 leading-[1.45] text-2xl">
          Prompt injection appears as a distinct category for the first time in this dataset. It is structurally similar to SQL injection: user-controlled strings concatenated into a sensitive context, a system prompt instead of a SQL query. Expect this class to rise in subsequent quarterly snapshots as more production code paths route through LLMs.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
